# Modules for the Veyron initramfs. MODULES=list is set by the depthcharge boot
# method (its conf.d/depthcharge.conf), which is what makes this list the whole
# initramfs rather than a supplement to it.
#
# This lives under /usr/share rather than /etc/initramfs-tools/modules because
# that file is an initramfs-tools conffile: writing it before the package is
# installed makes dpkg treat it as a locally-modified conffile and prompt.
# mkinitramfs reads modules.d/* unconditionally ("MODULES=list case. Always
# honour."), so a drop-in here has the same effect and no packaging conflict.
#
# It sits on the SoC layer because reaching a root filesystem is the same problem
# on every board in the family: the same PMIC, the same MMC controller, the same
# USB controllers. Names are the .ko basenames from the kernel's modules.order --
# note the driver for the IO-domain regulator is io-domain, NOT
# rockchip_io_domain. initramfs-tools pulls each module's dependencies in
# automatically, so ext4 brings jbd2/crc16/crc32c and usbhid brings hid.

# The RK808 PMIC chain. These are DEVICE-TREE dependencies, not symbol
# dependencies, so nothing pulls them in automatically -- and without them the
# SD slot never powers up. rk3288-veyron.dtsi feeds sdmmc from two RK808 LDOs
# (vmmc = vcc33_sd = LDO_REG5, vqmmc = vccio_sd = LDO_REG4), so dw_mmc-rockchip
# defers its probe until those regulators exist; in an initramfs that cannot
# provide them the root device never appears and the boot hangs on the
# firmware's white screen. io-domain's supplies come from the same PMIC.
# Debian builds the rk8xx-i2c MFD core in; what it modularizes is the I2C bus
# driver beneath it and the regulator function on top. The full account is
# board-research/veyron/veyron-white-screen.md.
i2c-rk3x
rk808-regulator
# The RK808's 32 kHz clock output. Consumed by the wifi power sequence
# (sdio-pwrseq defers with "external clock not ready" without it -- observed on
# the panel on real hardware) and cheap enough to carry rather than leave as a
# confounder in every deferred-probe listing.
clk-rk808

# Root filesystem: ext4 on eMMC or an SD card, behind Rockchip's DesignWare MMC
# controller. mmc_block is built in (CONFIG_MMC_BLOCK=y), so it is not listed.
dw_mmc
dw_mmc-pltfm
dw_mmc-rockchip
io-domain
ext4

# Root on USB, which this firmware also boots (Ctrl+U reads USB sticks as
# readily as SD cards) and which is the only removable medium a Chromebit has at
# all. The RK3288's host ports are EHCI/OHCI platform controllers behind the
# Rockchip USB PHY; dwc2 covers the other two controllers -- and on the Chromebit
# dwc2 is the only one there is, since rk3288-veyron-mickey.dts disables both the
# EHCI controller and usb_host1 and leaves usb_otg in host mode. usb-storage/uas
# present the stick, sd_mod turns it into sdN. Hardware-verified gap: an
# initramfs without these on a USB boot enumerates eMMC and wifi happily and then
# waits forever for a root that cannot appear.
phy-rockchip-usb
ehci-platform
ohci-platform
dwc2
usb-storage
uas
sd_mod

# Input for a rescue shell, which the family needs in two flavours because it has
# two kinds of console.
#
# The laptops type through the ChromeOS EC, which hangs off spi0 -- so the SPI bus
# driver has to come too: cros_ec_spi without spi-rockchip binds nothing, and a
# rescue shell with no keyboard is indistinguishable from a hang.
spi-rockchip
cros_ec
cros_ec_spi
cros_ec_keyb
# The Chromebit has no EC and no built-in keyboard: rk3288-veyron-mickey.dts never
# includes rk3288-veyron-chromebook.dtsi, so spi0 stays disabled and the four
# modules above bind nothing there. Its only input is a USB keyboard -- which is
# also how its *firmware* reads Ctrl+U, since the Chromebit is the one board in the
# family whose depthcharge is built with USB HID. The initramfs needs the same
# driver to offer a shell anyone can type at. Carried on every board rather than
# only the Chromebit, because a USB keyboard is a real fallback on a laptop whose
# EC keyboard has failed and the two modules cost ~40 KB against megabytes of
# spare budget.
usbhid
hid-generic

# NO DISPLAY STACK in the standard image -- a headroom policy, not a size limit.
#
# The DRM stack (rockchipdrm + analogix_dp + panel + backlight) compresses to
# only ~575 KB of xz and fits under even the stock 16 MiB ceiling, but the forky
# payload already sits above 90% with it included, and kernels grow at every
# Debian update. The standard image therefore leaves it out and accepts a
# console that appears only after the real root mounts -- measured 8-10 s of
# white splash on a healthy boot. A C201 with libreboot has a 32 MiB ceiling
# (`--board speedy-libreboot`), which is the headroom to carry the display stack
# and watch the initramfs on the panel 2-3 s after Ctrl+U.
#
# Because a standard-image initramfs failure is invisible on these boards, three
# things back this list up: the rootfs stage asserts every module here resolves
# under the installed kernel AND lands in the built initrd (so a typo fails the
# build, not the boot); the signed cmdline carries panic=30 (so a failed boot
# visibly reboots to the splash rather than hanging on a white screen); and
# scripts/panic/boot2deb-breadcrumb writes the full dmesg to every reachable ext4
# partition before that reboot.
